        <fig id="article-58723.image.f2" position="float" orientation="portrait">
          <caption>
            <p>Lower eyelid Anatomy: anatomy of the lateral canthal tendon. The lateral canthal tendon attaches the upper and lower tarsal plates to Whitnall's tubercle. The lateral canthal tendon insert 10 mm inferior to the zygomaticofrontal suture (range 5 - 15 mm). The lateral canthal tendon measures 7.5 mm from the lateral commisure to the lateral orbital attachment. The lateral canthus is attached approximately 1.35 mm higher than the medial canthus Contributed by Prof. Bhupendra C K Patel MD, FRCS</p>
          </caption>
          <graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="Lateral__canthal__anatomy" position="float" orientation="portrait"/>
        </fig>
      </floats-group>
      <floats-group id="article-58723.s13">
        <fig id="article-58723.image.f3" position="float" orientation="portrait">
          <caption>
            <p>Lower Eyelid Cross-sectional anatomy: the medial canthal tendon has an anterior reflection with inserts to the anterior lacrimal crest and a posterior limb which attaches to the posterior lacrimal crest. It is the attachment of the posterior limb that allows the lower eyelid to hug the globe. The lateral canthal tendon has the important posterior limb which attaches to the periosteum of the Whitnall's tubercle and the anterior limb which is termed the lateral palpebral raphe and spreads out to insert widely over the anterior lateral orbital rim and fans superiorly and inferiorly Contributed by Prof. Bhupendra C K Patel MD, FRCS</p>
          </caption>
          <graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="Cross__section__eyelid__anatomy-BCK__Patel" position="float" orientation="portrait"/>
        </fig>
      </floats-group>
